Terminology for this paper:
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Light is the visible portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
  
  \item ``spectrum'' means a range of wavelengths.
  
  \item ``spectra'' are several ranges of wavelengths.

  \item Light is a form of useful energy. Illumination is an energy service.
  
  \item Lamps are devices that convert electricity into light.
  
  \item To avoid ambiguity, we should not use ``lights'' to mean ``lamps.''

  \item Always be specific about energy and exergy.  
        Any time you use the words energy or exergy, be sure you mean it.  
        If you mean either, say ``energy or exergy.''

  \item Never use the word ``useful'' unless you mean the useful stage of the energy conversion chain.
  
  \item Let's be very clear about power and energy.  Use overdots ($\dot{X}$) to indicate powers (rates of energy).
  
  \item Review the nomenclature tables at the end of the paper.  
        If you use a new variable name, be sure you can't use a letter that already exists in the nomenclature tables.
        If you must use a new variable letter, add it to the table the first time you use it.
        
  \item Only single letters for main variable names.  
        Use subscripts to provide additional meaning.  
        Use decorations to indicate rates.
        
  \item The exergy-to-energy ratio ($\phi$) is \emph{not} second law efficiency ($\eta_X$)
        The energy-to-exergy ratio ($\phi$) applies at every statepoint.  
        $\eta_E$ and $\eta_X$ apply across energy conversion devices.
        
  \item Power is energy per time. watts are power.
  
  \item Spectral radiant power and radiant power refer to the electromagnetic radiation emitted 
        by a lamp as measured directly in Watts. Spectral luminous power and luminous power \emph{only} refer
        to the electromagnetic radiation emitted by a lamp as measured in lumens (by applying the photopic luminosity function,
        and multiplying by a factor of 683 lm/W)
  
  \item Flux is quantity per unit area per unit time. W/m$^2$ is a flux.
        
  \item Do not confuse power and flux.  Do not write ``radiant power/flux,''
        seemingly indicating that power and flux
        are synonyms.  Power and flux are not synonyms.

\end{enumerate}
