\subsubsection{Human perception of EM radiation} 
\label{sec:human_perception_of_EM_radiation}
%------------------------------

We noted above that both
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item \enaex{} of light and

  \item \enaex{} efficiency of lamps

\end{enumerate*}
%
are independent of human presence.
But what about human \emph{perception}?

Human beings perceive heat by temperature and light by wavelength.
Human skin can perceive the thermal radiation portion of the broader electromagnetic spectrum,
approximately 100 nm < $\lambda$ < 10,000 nm. 
Furthermore, human skin is differentially sensitive to EM spectrum wavelength.  
Indeed, thermoreceptors in the dermis of skin are important sensors for regulation of body temperature.
