%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy-to-energy ratio of EM radiation, $\phi_{\EM}$ (Zeke and Emmanuel, 500 words)}
\label{sec:phi_light}
%------------------------------

Recent advances in the thermodynamics of radiation community
enable converting the energy of EM radiation into the exergy of EM radiation.
The exergy-to-energy ratio of EM radiation
($\phi_{\EM}$, called the ``radiative exergy-energy coefficient'' in that community)
is given by Petela's Equation~\cite{petela1964exergy}:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:petelas_equation}
 \phi_{\EM} = 1 - \frac{4}{3}\frac{T_{0}}{T_{1}} + \frac{1}{3} \left(\frac{T_{0}}{T_{1}}\right)^4 \; .
\end{equation}

However, Petela's equation assumes a blackbody emitter and
a blackbody absorber 
at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_0$, respectively.
To determine $\phi_{\EM}$ for a non-blackbody lamp,
the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio ($\phi_{\EM,\lambda}$),
must be calculated.
An effective temperature of light photons~\cite{chen2008} ($T_\lambda$) 
provides the link between Petela's equation (Equation~\ref{eq:petelas_equation})
and the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_{\EM,\lambda}$).

Petela's equation has recently been verified through the development of an infinite-staged
Carnot engine model \cite{zhou2017exergy}, which describes the transfer of radiative energy.
In this model a photon possessing a characteristic frequency 
and photon effective temperature enters a medium which acts as an ideal absorber. 
The photon transfers an infinitesimal quantity of thermal radiation to the absorber, 
this thermal radiation then enters a Carnot heat engine and performs work. 
The absorber then emits another photon at a lower energy and frequency 
(and therefore lower photon effective temperature). 
This process is repeated until the frequency of the photon equals zero, 
and $T_0$ (the reference temperature) is equal to the photon effective temperature ($T_\lambda$)~\cite{Shan2019}.

We note that the use of the photon effective temperature approach has been criticized by 
\citet[p.~1810]{liu2009},
who argued that 
``to endue a single photon with macro-scale thermodynamic parameters
such as exergy and entropy'' is inappropriate.
We acknowledge this critique, 
but we also note that here $T_\lambda$ is ascribed to a stream of photons
traveling from a lamp to an eye.
Thus, for our purposes, $T_\lambda$ can be considered the statistical average effective temperature 
of the stream of photons.
****
Is this a good way to address the critique?---MKH
****
The product of wavelength and photon effective temperature is a constant~($c_3$ in \citet{chen2008}) such that
%
\begin{equation}
  \lambda T_{\lambda} = c_{3} = 5.33016 \times 10^{-3} \text{ m-K} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
or
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:T_lambda}
  T_\lambda = \frac{5.33016 \times 10^{-3} \text{ m-K}}{\lambda} \; .
\end{equation}

We make the assumption that the mechanism
by which light is converted into electrical nerve signals
in the human eye
is radiative EM energy transfer
from a light source~(1) to an eye~(0).
We further assume that the human iris is a blackbody absorber 
(absorbing all wavelengths of radiation perfectly \cite{benenson2006handbook}), 
being a small aperture on a larger cavity.
(In this assumption, we follow \citet[p.~172]{Rossing2020} who state
``another good example of [a blackbody absorber] is the human eye;
the pupil looks black because most light entering it is trapped and absorbed.'')
Thus, we use Shan and Zhou's~\cite{Shan2019} spectral formulation of Petela's equation,
which replaces the temperature of the emitter ($T_1$) by photon effective temperature~($T_\lambda$):
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:phi_EM_lambda_shan_zhou}
 \phi_{\EM,\lambda} = 1 - \frac{4}{3} \left( \frac{T_{0}}{T_{\lambda}} \right)
                        + \frac{1}{3} \left(\frac{T_{0}}{T_{\lambda}}\right)^4 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Further, Equation~\ref{eq:T_lambda} can be substituted into Equation~\ref{eq:phi_EM_lambda_shan_zhou}
(in the form $T_\lambda = c_3 / \lambda$),
and $T_0$ can be taken as 310~K, the temperature of the human body.
The result is an equation for $\phi_{L,\lambda}$, the specular exergy-to-energy ratio of light:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:phi_L_lambda_shan_zhou}
 \phi_{L,\lambda} = 1 
                    - \frac{4}{3} \left( \frac{310 \text{ K}}{c_3} \right) \lambda 
                    + \frac{1}{3} \left( \frac{310 \text{ K}}{c_3} \right)^4 \lambda^4 \; .
\end{equation}

We assume no losses in radiative transmission
between the lamp and the iris.
I.e., no radiation scattering occurs through air, 
an assumption that holds for short distances typically 
observed in lighting applications (<~10~m).
(See \citet{Shan2019} for a method to estimate transmission losses
over longer distances.)

The exergy of light emitted by a non-blackbody lamp~($\dot{X}_L$)
is found by integrating the product of
the spectral radiant power~($\Phi_{EM,\lambda}$),
a spectral weighting function~($f_\lambda$), and
the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_\lambda$)
with respect to wavelength.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:X_dot_L}
  \dot{X}_L = \int \phi_{L,\lambda} \, f_\lambda \, \Phi_{EM,\lambda} \mathrm{d}\lambda
\end{equation}

The quotient of $\dot{X}_{L}$ and $\dot{L}$ gives the overall exergy-energy ratio of light~($\phi_{L}$), 
which is specific to each combination of
lamp and weighting function ($f_\lambda \Phi_{EM,\lambda}$).

\begin{equation} \label{eq:phi_L}
  \phi_{L} = \frac{\dot{X}_L}{\dot{L}} 
           = \frac {\int \phi_{L,\lambda} f_\lambda \Phi_{EM,\lambda} \mathrm{d}\lambda}
                       {\int f_\lambda \Phi_{EM,\lambda} \mathrm{d}\lambda}
\end{equation}

