(See Section~\ref{sec:human_perception_of_EM_radiation}.)
We selected four spectral weighting functions relevant to illumination
to enable example calculations later (Section~\ref{sec:results}).

The first option is degenerate: 
the analyst could decide to ignore the nuances of human visual perception altogether,
implicitly assuming that all EM radiation emitted from a lamp is valuable, 
whether or not it is within the visible portion of the EM spectrum.
For the first option, the degenerate (unweighted, uw) weighting function ($f_{\lambda,uw}$) is
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f1}
  f_{\lambda,uw} = 1 \; .
\end{equation}

Second, the analyst could 
deem a lamp's EM radiation to be useful if and only if it \emph{could}
stimulate photoreceptive cells in the human eye,
regardless of the spectral sensitivity of those cells.
In the second option, the analyst excludes wavelengths outside the range of perception by the human eye
when determining the \enoex{} of light.
For the second option (visible, vis),
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f2}
f_{\lambda,vis} =
  \begin{cases}
    0 \; , & \text{for } \lambda < 380 \text{ nm} \\
    1 \; , & \text{for } 380 \text{ nm} \le \lambda \le 750 \text{ nm} \\
    0 \; , & \text{for } 750 \text{ nm} < \lambda \\
  \end{cases} \; .
\end{equation}

But the human eye is spectrally sensitive to EM radiation, 
with peak sensitivity at 555~nm (green)
and lesser sensitivities at both longer and shorter wavelengths.
A third option involves weighting a lamp's emitted EM radiation 
by the photopic sensitivity of the human eye.
The photopic luminosity~(pl) function~($V_\lambda$) describes this sensitivity, 
as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:Vis_Graph}.
The photopic luminosity function was
defined by the Commission Internationale de l' Ã‰clairage (CIE) and 
represents the sensitivity of M and L cones
at daytime light levels \cite{CVRL2008}.
So for Option 3,
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f3}
  f_{\lambda,pl} = V_\lambda \; .
\end{equation}

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:f3} into Equation~\ref{eq:weighted_emissive_power}
yields
%
\begin{equation}
  \dot{L}_{pl} = \int V_\lambda \Phi_{EM,\lambda} \mathrm{d}\lambda \; ,
\end{equation}
%
which provides the basis for calculating a lamp's output 
of visible light in the unit of lumens~(lm, $\Phi_{pl}$):
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:lumen}
  \Phi_{pl} = (683 \text{ lm/W}) \; \dot{L}_{pl} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where 683~lm/W is the EM power of a perfect light source emitting at $\lambda = 555 \text{ nm}$.
(See Figure~\ref{fig:Vis_Graph}.) 
(Note that because lumens are a re-scaling of watts, 
lumens are also a unit of radiant power.)

When the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$) is used 
to calculate luminous power, 
the valuable energy efficiency of a lamp can be written in terms of luminous efficacy~($K$)
by modifying Equation~\ref{eq:eta_E_v_light} to be
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:lum_effic_def}
  K = \frac{(683 \text{ lm/W}) \int V_\lambda \Phi_{EM,\lambda,3} \mathrm{d}\lambda}{\dot{W}_1}
\end{equation}
%
in the context of Figure~\ref{fig:lamp}, 
where $K$ is in lm/watt.

The photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$) is the industry standard for determining lumen output
of lamps, but it has been criticized for under-representing
the power of wavelengths different from 555~nm. 
In fact, the photopic luminosity function
neglects the differential sensitivity of the human eye's other light receptors,
namely the short-wave cones,
rods, and intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (ipRGCs),
which are responsible for vision in low-light settings and
physiological functions such as the regulation of circadian rhythms.
Thus, the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$) 
is said to have a long-wave bias.

A fourth option (universal, univ) weights a lamp's spectral radiant power~($\Phi_{EM,\lambda}$)
by the spectral sensitivity of all five light receptors in the human eye
(not just the M and L cones as does $V_\lambda$). 
The universal luminosity efficiency function ($U_\lambda$) \cite{Rea2018}
captures the actual, broader sensitivity of the human eye.
So, for option 4,
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:f4}
  f_{\lambda,univ} = U_\lambda \; .
\end{equation}

Table~\ref{tab:wfs} summarizes the weighting functions discussed above.

