\subsubsection{Lamps}
\label{sec:lamps}
%------------------------------

To demonstrate how the use of selection of spectral weighting function~($f_\lambda$)
alters the efficiency of a lamp, 
we need both weighting functions (Section~\ref{sec:weighting_functions}) and
example lamps.
Table~\ref{tab:lamps} summarizes details about lamps discussed throughout this paper.

We obtained spectral power distributions of the lamps in Table~\ref{tab:lamps} from the 
Light Spectral Power Distribution Database (LSPDD)~\cite{Roby, miguel2017, aube2013}. 

The data in the LSPDD are given 
in terms of \emph{relative intensity} ($\Phi_{rel,e\lambda}$) 
as opposed to \emph{absolute intensity}.
Because lamps in the LSPDD are not measured using an integration sphere,
the integral of the spectral power distribution may not match the radiant power of the lamp
supplied by the manufacturer.
To ensure that the integral of each lamp's spectral power distribution 
matches its reported radiant power, 
we applied the standard procedure of scaling the spectral power distribution 
by the ratio ($\mu$) of
the radiant power given by the manufacturer~($K \dot{W}_1$) and  
the integral of the spectral radiant power taken from the relative intensity data~($\Phi_{rel,EM}$).
%
\begin{equation} 
  \mu = \frac{K \dot{W}_1}{\Phi_{rel,EM}}   \; .
\end{equation}

We then applied the scaling factor~($\mu$) to to the spectral power distribution data for each lamp, 
yielding a scaled spectral power distribution data for each lamp 
that matches the manufacturer's reported radiant power ($\Phi_{EM,\lambda}$),
%
\begin{equation} 
  \Phi_{EM,\lambda}  = \mu \Phi_{rel,EM,\lambda}   \; .
\end{equation}

We selected one representative lamp for four common lamp technologies
(incandescent, INC;
high pressure sodium, HPS;
compact fluorescent, CFL; and
light emitting diode, LED), 
each with a unique spectral power distribution,
allowing for clear comparisons 
of the effects of spectral weighting functions~($f_\lambda$) and
the spectral exergy-to-energy ratio~($\phi_\lambda$).


