\subsection{Weighting functions and blue light}
\label{sec:blue_light}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Previously, societal exergy analysis implicitly adopted the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
when calculating the exergetic efficiency of lighting.
(See Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach}.)

Given that the industry-standard measure of lighting efficiency
is the luminous efficacy~($K$),
the use of the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
under-represents the power at short wavelengths in lighting efficiency estimates.
This state of affairs biases lighting manufacturers to reduce short wavelength
output of lamps, even when short wavelength EM radiation would be beneficial
for physiological reasons such as the suppression of melanopsin 
the regulation of circadian rhythms \cite{Pattison2018LEDphotons}.

To account for this many lamps are designed to have 'blue spike', 
emitting radiant energy in the region of 480nm, 
the peak of the melanopsin suppression action spectrum \cite{lucas2014}, 
as can be seen from the spectral power distribution~($\Phi_{EM,\lambda}$)
for the LED lamp in Figure \ref{fig:wfs_and_lamps}. 

To more accurately quantify the utility of different wavelengths of light,
the universal luminosity function has been proposed 
as a replacement for the photopic luminosity function, because it 
accounts for the sensitivity of all five of the eyes light receptors 
as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:human_perception_of_EM_radiation}.

The choice of weighting function should be made appropriate for the application of each lamp.
To provide consistency for societal exergy analysis community moving forward
we propose that societal exergy analysts 
adopt the universal luminosity function ($U_\lambda$) in accordance with \cite{Rea2018},
when lamps are used solely for illumination in society.
The switch from the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$)
to the universal luminosity function~($U_\lambda$) is made possible 
by the exact method described in Section~\ref{sec:framework}. 
The approximate method requires the use of the photopic luminosity function~($V_\lambda$),
as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach}.

