\subsection{Further challenges}
\label{sec:further_challenges}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

There are two challenges facing the societal exergy analyst regarding
the exergy of light, namely
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item how to account for waste heat from lamps and
  
  \item how to account for waste light from lamps.

\end{enumerate*}
%
We discuss each challenge in the sections below.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Waste heat from lamps}
\label{sec:waste_heat}
%------------------------------

Every lamp produces waste heat ($\dot{Q}_2$ in Figure~\ref{fig:lamp})
as it converts electrical energy into light energy. 
The efficiency describing this process is often referred to as the \emph{first law efficiency} or \emph{wall plug efficiency}.
In this analysis the proportion of heat generated by a lamp is given by 
$1-\eta_{i,uw}$ or $1-\frac{\Phi_{i,uw}}{\dot{W}_{1}}$.


**** Shall we report the proportion of heat, and IR radiation that a lamp generates 
in an additional results table? ---ZM ****


In Section~\ref{sec:energy_and_exergy_of_light}
waste heat was deemed the un-valuable product of the lamp.
However, in some circumstances, the waste heat from lamps is, in fact, valuable,
because it displaces energy for space heating,
especially in winter climates.
In summer climates, waste heat from lamps adds to space cooling loads.
For locations where both summer cooling and winter heating are performed,
the winter/summer effects of lamps cancel, to first order.

The societal exergy analyst must decide how to treat waste heat from lamps
when determining the quantity of useful energy delivered to a society.
To our knowledge, societal exergy analysis has, to date,
ignored waste heat from lamps,
implicitly assuming that winter and summer effects cancel.
We contend that the issue deserves further study,
but that is a topic for another paper.

In addition to the thermal heat generated by a lamp, 
some lamps, commonly termed heat lamps, infrared lamps or infrared heaters are
explicitly designed to produce radiative heat 
(light in the form of near and far infrared radiation) 
for various purposes, including
space heating, incubator heating, plastic manufacture, 
food preparation, and warming animals in captivity.

As the infrared portion of light emitted as radiative heat is considered useful 
common ceramic infrared heaters have final to useful energy efficiencies of 56.7~\% \cite{brown2016} when emitting radiative heat,
with the remainder of the energy (43.3~\%) converted into thermal heat, 
which may or may not be considered useful 
as the mechanism of thermal heat transfer acts over a shorter distance (convection).

