%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Waste light from lamps (MKH and ZM)}
\label{sec:waste_light}
%------------------------------

In the exact method of this study,
light is considered wasted if it either outside of the range of wavelengths
in a spectral weighting function~($f_\lambda$), or
within a wavelength of light for which the radiant power has been reduced as a result of a weighting function.
The portion of light not wasted is termed the valuable light ($\Phi_v$).

This mechanism is discussed in Section~\ref{sec:effect_weighting_functions}.

However, our framework assumes that all of the valuable light emitted by a lamp is utilised. 
Two further losses occur before the valuable light is available for work \cite{CullenPhD}.
%
\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item Losses within the luminaire (lamp housing) - 
        where a proportion of light never exits the device.
   
  \item Light which is incident upon surfaces which do not need to be illuminated
        such as ceilings. Together with luminaire losses, 
        this is quantified by the luminaire output ratio.

\end{enumerate}
%
Furthermore, there are three additional passive losses of light, as detailed by \citet{CullenPhD}.
%
\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item Light which is emitted with an excessive intensity.
   
  \item Light which is incident upon surfaces which are not the primary purpose of illumination.
  
  \item Light which is under-utilised, e.g. through under-occupancy.
       

\end{enumerate}
%

Accounting for all of these potential efficiency savings in a commercial office lighting scenario
\citet{CullenPhD} estimates the upper limit for energy savings to be 95~\%.

