In the context of SEA, and the energy conversion chain, 
these losses occur at the \emph{energy service} stage, 
after the conversion of electricity to radiant power or light. 
As such we deem further analysis of these passive efficiency losses 
beyond the scope of our study.



%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Application for country-level societal exergy analysis}
\label{sec:Application}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

To move from the final to useful energy/exergy efficiency of a single lamp, 
to either an economy-wide or sectoral aggregate lighting efficiency, 
several types of data are required for the given period of study:

\begin{enumerate}[label={(\alph*)}]

  \item Final to useful efficiency data for each lamp technology
  \item Energy to exergy ratios for each of the corresponding lamp technologies
  \item Electricity consumption by lamp technology

\end{enumerate}

Items $a$ and $b$ are rarely reported for lamps, nor is the associated SPD data.
Instead the most common measure of lighting efficiency reported for lamps is the luminous efficacy.
Therefore, to develop an aggregate measure of lighting efficiency, 
luminous efficacy data must be converted into final to useful efficiency values.
As demonstrated in Section~\ref{sec:previous_approach} if the \emph{valuable} light
is deemed to be the radiant power weighted by the photopic luminosity function 
(luminous power, $\Phi_{pl}$),
the final to useful efficiencies are equivalent to the luminous efficiency, 
namely $\frac{K}{683 lm/W}$.
In the absence of SPD data an exergy to energy ratio for each technology type must be selected,
as the shape of lamp SPD's display relatively little variation within technology groups
compared to between groups, 
the aggregate exergy to energy ratios for those lamps also display little variation.

