Once efficiency series have been calculated
and exergy to energy ratios obtained for each lamp type,
data for the proportion of each lamp type in use for each year of the study is needed,
i.e. the fleet of lamps, 
and ideally in the form of electricity consumption by lighting technology.
For example, tHe US DOE's Lighting Market Characterization reports provide such data for the USA,
and for the years 2001~\cite{DOE2002}, 2010~\cite{DOE2012}, and 2015~\cite{DOE2017}, 
along with associated luminous efficacy values, 
and for the following lamp technologies: incandescent, halogen, compact fluorescent,
linear fluorescent, high intensity discharge, LED and other.

The aggregate lighting efficiency for a particular year is then given by

\begin{equation} \label{eq:agg_eta}
  \eta_{agg} = \sum \limits_{i \in Lamps} \theta_{i,pl} \cdot \phi_{i,pl} \cdot \eta_{E,i,pl} 
\end{equation}

Where $\theta_{i}$ denotes the proportion of electricity consumption for lighting
by a particular lamp technology for a given year.

